FERC ELECTRIC TARIFF
1) Availability
Seller makes electric energy, capacity, and ancillary services available under this Tariff to any purchaser, except as prohibited below.
2) Rates
All sales shall be made at rates established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller.
3) Other Terms and Conditions
All other terms and conditions for sales under this Tariff shall be established by agreement between Seller and purchaser.
4) Seller Category
Seller is a Category 2 Seller in the Northeast Region and is a Category 1 Seller in all other regions as defined in 18 CFR 35.36(a).
5) Compliance with Commission Regulations
Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning Seller's market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes Seller to engage in affiliate sales under this Tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the Seller's market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning Seller's market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this Tariff.
6) Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority
Seller has received waiver of: Subparts B and C of Part 35, except for sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15 and 35.16; Part 41, Part 101 (with the exception that any waiver of the provisions of Part 101 that apply to hydropower licenses is not granted with respect to licensed hydropower projects), and Part 141, except sections 141.14 and 141.15.; and received blanket approval pursuant to Federal Power Act Section 204 and Part 34 of the Commission's regulations. Great Bay Solar I, LLC, Docket No. ER17-2084 (Letter Order issued August 25, 2017).
7) Ancillary Services
PJM: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. ("PJM") and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection.
New York: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute non-synchronous, 30-minute operating reserves, 10-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc.
New England: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc.
California: Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation ("CAISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO.
MISO: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. (MISO) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to MISO.
Southwest Power Pool: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. (SPP) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to SPP.
Third-party ancillary services: Seller offers Regulation Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, Operating Reserve Supplemental, and Primary Frequency Response Service. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider's OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization.
8) Revisions
Seller may file revisions of this Tariff with the Commission. Nothing contained in this Tariff shall be construed as affecting or limiting in any way the right of Seller to unilaterally file with the Commission for a change in any aspect of this Tariff under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act pursuant to the Commission's Rules and Regulations.
9) Effective Date
This Tariff shall become effective on the date specified by the Commission.

GREAT BAY SOLAR I, LLC RATE SCHEDULE FERC NO. 2
Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generation Sources Service
Great Bay Solar I, LLC ("Great Bay") provides Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generation Sources Service ("Reactive Supply Service") from a solar generating facility located in Somerset County, Maryland within the Delmarva Power & Light Company ("DP&L") Zone of the control area administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. ("PJM") in order to assist in maintaining transmission voltages within acceptable limits on the PJM transmission system. This Rate Schedule sets forth Great Bay's revenue requirements for the provision of Reactive Supply Service, as contemplated by Schedule 2 of the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff, which provides that PJM will pay generation owners their monthly revenue requirement for Reactive Supply Service. This Rate Schedule shall be effective upon the date authorized by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT This Shared Facilities Agreement ("Agreement") is made and entered into on this 19th day of December, 2019 ("Effective Date") by and among Great Bay Solar I, LLC, a Maryland limited liability company ("Phase I Owner") and Great Bay Solar II, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ("Phase II Owner", and, together with Phase I Owner, the "Parties" and each such person individually, a "Party"). Certain capitalized terms used in this Agreement are given defined meanings in Appendix A attached hereto. RECITALS A. Phase I Owner owns and operates a solar energy generation facility with a capacity of 75 megawatts ("MW") alternating current ("AC") in Somerset County, Maryland ("Phase I Project"); B. Phase II Owner is developing, and upon completion will own and operate a solar energy generation facility with a capacity of up to 43 megawatts MW AC in Somerset County, Maryland ("Phase II Project"); C. Phase I Owner is a party to that certain Interconnection Service Agreement dated June 26, 2015, with PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. and Delmarva Power and Light Company ("Interconnection Agreement"); D. Phase II Owner (either directly or through Affiliates) contemplates developing one or more additional solar generation facilities, with a capacity of up to the remaining Maximum Facility Output (as defined in the Interconnection Agreement) after Phase II Project is operating ("Subsequent Phase Projects", together with the Phase I Project and the Phase II Project, the "Projects" and each a "Project"); E. Phase I Owner also owns, as part of the Phase I Project, 100% of certain electrical power transmission, communications, and interconnection facilities, as more particularly described in Exhibit A-1 attached hereto ("Shared Facilities"), which have been constructed on the Shared Premises. F. Phase I Owner wishes to grant Phase II Owner the right to use and maintain, with one or more Project Owners, the Shared Facilities, that portion of the rights under the Interconnection Agreement necessary for the Phase II Project and any Subsequent Phase Project, and portions of the Shared Premises (as defined below) that are necessary for the construction and operation of the Phase II Project and any Subsequent Phase Project; G. For purposes of this Agreement, "Shared Premises Agreements" shall mean those real property rights held by one or more of the Project Owners necessary to access and use the Shared Premises for the operation of their respective Projects, as more particularly described in Exhibit A-2 attached hereto, and as amended from time to time, pursuant to the terms and conditions of this Agreement. The "Shared Premises" shall mean the real property upon, over, or under which the Shared Facilities are located, as more particularly described in Exhibit A-3 attached hereto. The Shared Facilities Manager shall update Exhibits A-1, A-2, and A-3 from time to time in order to set forth the Shared Facilities, Shared Premises, and the Shared Premises Agreements applicable to this Agreement. H. Phase II Owner desires to reserve certain rights with respect to the Shared Facilities hereunder for the use and/or development of Subsequent Phase Projects, whereby in furtherance of the use or development of each Subsequent Phase Project, Phase II Owner may assign to the owner of a Subsequent Phase Project all or a portion of such reserved rights, as provided herein. AGREEMENT NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the foregoing recitals, the mutual promises contained herein, and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and adequacy of which are hereby acknowledged by the Parties, the Parties hereby agree as follows: ARTICLE 1 SHARED FACILITIES AND INTERCONNECTION 1.1 Right to Shared Facilities. Phase I Owner hereby grants to Phase II Owner, during the term of this Agreement, and on the terms and subject to the conditions of this Agreement, the non-exclusive right to access and use the Shared Facilities as may be reasonably necessary in connection with the ownership, construction, operation, and maintenance of the Phase II Project. The rights of the Parties shall include the joint use of the Shared Facilities (whether now existing or hereafter acquired or constructed) to the full extent necessary for each Project to operate at its capacity, including to the extent such Shared Facilities (whether now existing or hereafter acquired or constructed) constitute fixtures under Applicable Law. 1.2 Sharing of Interconnection Service. Of the 150 MW AC of capacity available under the Interconnection Agreement, 75 MW AC shall be used for the interconnection and operation of the Phase I Project, up to 43 MW AC shall be used for the interconnection and operation of the Phase II Project, and the remaining approximately 32 MW AC shall be reserved to Phase II Owner for one or more Subsequent Phase Projects (such reserved capacity, "Reserved Interconnection"). 1.3 Subsequent Phase Owner Reserved Rights. (a) Phase I Owner hereby grants to Phase II Owner, to the extent required in connection with the development, construction, maintenance, replacement, or operation of one or more Subsequent Phase Projects, during the term of this Agreement and on the terms and subject to the conditions of this Agreement, the non-exclusive right to access and use the Shared Facilities in accordance with the terms and conditions set forth in this Agreement as may be reasonably necessary in connection with the ownership, operation, and maintenance of the Subsequent Phase Project(s) (together with the right to use the Reserved Interconnection, the "Reserved Rights"). (b) Phase II Owner shall have the express right to (i) develop, construct, operate, maintain, expand, own, finance, and sell one or more Subsequent Phase Projects, and (ii) transfer all or any portion of its Reserved Rights in accordance with the terms and conditions of this Agreement, including Section 10.2, provided that the exercise of such rights is in accordance with the terms of the then-effective PJM Tariff and shall not result in the breach of any of the terms and conditions of this Agreement. Phase II Owner may exercise its right to transfer any portion of its Reserved Rights on multiple occasions and to multiple assignees; provided, that, such transfers are made pursuant to, and in accordance with the terms and conditions of, this Agreement, including Section 10.2, the terms of the then-effective PJM Tariff, and that such assignee ("Subsequent Phase Owner") executes and delivers a joinder to this Agreement in a form substantially similar to that attached hereto as Exhibit C ("Joinder"). Phase II Owner shall give Phase I Owner 30 days' prior written notice of any proposed Joinder to provide Phase I Owner the opportunity to dispute whether the proposed Joinder complies with this Agreement; provided, however, that for the purpose of clarity, so long as the transfer in question is being made in accordance with the terms and conditions of this Agreement, including Section 10.2, the terms of the then-effective PJM Tariff, Phase I Owner's right to dispute the Joinder shall be limited to analysis of whether or not such Joinder is substantially similar to the form of Joinder attached hereto as Exhibit C. Phase II Owner shall not be deemed to have assigned all of its Reserved Rights in accordance with the terms and conditions of this Agreement unless, in connection with a transfer, Phase II Owner provides written notice to Phase I Owner that Phase II Owner is expressly relinquishing all of its Reserved Rights. Each of Phase II Owner and Phase I Owner shall take commercially reasonable actions and enter into all agreements and other documents (in each case in form and substance reasonably acceptable to each Party) as are reasonably necessary to share such Shared Facilities with each applicable Subsequent Phase Owner (all at Phase II Owner's or such Subsequent Phase Owner's cost) in accordance with the applicable terms and conditions of this Agreement. Without limiting the foregoing, upon the request of Phase II Owner or a Subsequent Phase Owner in connection with use of the Shared Facilities by a Subsequent Phase Project, each applicable Project Owner shall assist Phase II Owner or Subsequent Phase Owner (at Phase II Owner's or Subsequent Phase Owner's cost) in obtaining approvals from applicable permitting authorities, consultants, landowners and other third parties to the extent reasonably required to enable such Subsequent Phase Project to benefit from and rely on such agreements and other documents. 1.4 Vesting. The right to access and use the Shared Facilities granted by Phase I Owner to Phase II Owner by this Agreement shall vest in Phase II Owner as a contracting party to this Agreement without any transfer of title, leasehold or other interest in the Shared Facilities; provided, that, neither Phase II Owner nor any Subsequent Phase Owner shall have the right to use or access the Shared Facilities or Shared Premises until (i) all real estate rights and permits that are required for such Project Owner's access to and use of the Shared Facilities have been obtained; (ii) the applicable Project Owner has taken all steps required to be taken on or prior to such use or access of the Shared Facilities or Shared Premises in order to obtain and has obtained every regulatory approval from all applicable Governmental Authorities having jurisdiction that are required for such Project Owner's development, construction, operation and interconnection of its Project and its access to and use of the Shared Facilities; and (iii) the Project Owner would not be in breach or default of any term or provision of this Agreement, any Applicable Law or any Project Agreement or other material contract to which it is party; provided, that notwithstanding the foregoing, Phase II Owner may operate and interconnect its Project and access and use the Shared Facilities and Shared Premises prior to receipt of the approval by FERC of the effective date of this Agreement pursuant to the Federal Power Act Section 205 and Part 35 of the FERC regulation. Nothing in this agreement shall be construed to establish a partnership or joint venture between the Parties. 1.5 Real Property and Permits. Each Project Owner agrees to use commercially reasonable efforts to reasonably assist any other Project Owner in its effort to obtain those real property rights as is reasonably necessary for the Project Owner to access and use the Shared Premises and to carry out its rights and obligations hereunder with respect to the Shared Facilities. Except as otherwise provided in this Section 1.5 or as otherwise included in this Agreement, (a) each Project Owner shall be solely responsible for obtaining and maintaining all third-party and governmental permits, licenses, and real property rights necessary for such Project Owner's access to and from and use and maintenance of the Shared Premises and Shared Facilities, and (b) this Agreement shall not be construed as a grant of any real property right by any Project Owner to any other Project Owner to access or use the Shared Facilities, the Shared Premises, or any portion thereof. This Agreement provides a contractual right to use the Shared Facilities themselves, once each Project Owner has obtained all governmental permits and real property rights necessary for such Project Owner's access to and from and use and maintenance of the Shared Premises and Shared Facilities. A Project Owner shall provide a true, correct, and complete copy of any Shared Premises Agreements to which such Project Owner is a party upon request by another Party. Each Project Owner shall be responsible for the payment of any rent or other fees, and the performance of any obligations, to any non-Affiliate third party pursuant to the terms and conditions of the Shared Premises Agreement to which it is a party. If a Project Owner pays any amounts to, or performs any obligations for any non-Affiliate third party relating to the other Project Owner's Project, including without limitation payments and obligations relating to Gross Revenues or Project Property (as such terms are defined in the applicable Shared Premises Agreements), then such other Project Owner shall reimburse the paying or performing Project Owner within ten (10) Business Days of such payment or performance. 1.6 Access to Shared Facilities. Each Project Owner shall have access to the Shared Facilities (a) for inspection of the Shared Facilities, (b) for any required maintenance of the Shared Facilities agreed to be undertaken by the Project Owner that is not performed by the Shared Facilities Manager in accordance with Section 12.3 below and (c) for repairs of the Shared Facilities, all in accordance with this Agreement. Each Project Owner shall follow all applicable safety, security, prior notice, and site rules established by the Shared Facilities Manager, and shall comply with all applicable Shared Premises Agreements, Applicable Law, and Prudent Industry Practice when on the Shared Premises or accessing the Shared Facilities. 1.7 Installation or Construction Conditions and Costs. Phase II Owner and any Subsequent Phase Owner, each as applicable, shall (i) limit any interference with the use by Phase I Owner of the Shared Facilities or its Separate Facilities and the Phase I Project during any installation or construction of the Phase II Project or Subsequent Phase Project and (ii) except in the event of an Emergency, (a) schedule during a down-time if possible, or, as a second choice, during an off-peak period if possible, any required disconnection of the Shared Facilities or Separate Facilities to conduct installation or any construction activities in order to minimize the impact on the Phase I Project, and (b) provide prior written notice to Phase I Owner of commencement of such activities together with a reasonably detailed description thereof, including dates and times or such activities and disconnection, if any. Phase II Owner and any Subsequent Phase Owner, as applicable, shall reimburse to Phase I Owner its Pro Rata Share for (x) all Net Lost Profits accrued by the Phase I Project during the period of disconnection arising from the installation or construction of the Phase II Project or any Subsequent Phase Project, and (y) any panel washing at the Phase I Project necessitated (as reasonably determined by the Phase I Owner) by work relating to the installation or construction of the Phase II Project or any Subsequent Phase Project. The Parties acknowledge and agree that, subject to Section 14.1(a)(iv), (1) the reimbursement for Net Lost Profits and panel washing costs shall be Phase I Owner's sole and exclusive remedy with respect to a loss of revenue and other Consequential Damages due to the period of disconnection, (2) the actual Consequential Damages arising due to such period of disconnection would be difficult to compute and (3) the methodology for determining such damages set forth above is a good faith estimate of the calculations used to determine the actual Consequential Damages that would be suffered by Phase I Owner. ARTICLE 2 REPLACEMENT OF SHARED FACILITIES 2.1 Repair and Replacement of Shared Facilities. (a) The Project Owners hereby authorize Shared Facilities Manager to replace any component of the Shared Facilities with a Qualified Replacement Component, or to repair any component thereof, without seeking additional consent of the applicable Project Owners under this Agreement, if (i) Shared Facilities Manager reasonably estimates that the cost of the replacement or repair (including installation) will be equal to or less than $100,000 per occurrence or $500,000 in the aggregate per calendar year ("Permitted Capital Project Cost Cap") or (ii) Shared Facilities Manager determines that the replacement or repair is necessary to address an Emergency (any such replacement or repair, a "Permitted Capital Project"); provided, however, that, in the case of this clause (ii), if the cost of the Permitted Capital Project (including installation) exceeds the amount set forth in clause (i), notice of the Permitted Capital Project shall be given by Shared Facilities Manager to the other Project Owners as soon as reasonably practicable, but not to exceed 30 calendar days, after the estimated cost for the Permitted Capital Project is known by Shared Facilities Manager. No other notice of a Permitted Capital Project under this Section 2.1(a) shall be required except as such replacement or repair costs may be included in periodic financial and operating reports that may be required under this Agreement. The Permitted Capital Project Cost Cap shall be adjusted annually in accordance with the Inflation Adjustment, with the first adjustment taking effect on January 1, 2021. (b) Except as otherwise permitted by Section 2.1(a), the Shared Facilities Manager shall provide notice ("Capital Project Notice") in writing to the Project Owners of (i) any component of a Shared Facility that needs replacement, and the proposed replacement component, which shall be a Qualified Replacement Component, (ii) any Shared Facility or component thereof that needs repair, and (iii) the estimated cost (including installation) of such replacement or repair ("Proposed Capital Project"). If each of the Project Owners approves the Proposed Capital Project, the Shared Facilities Manager shall undertake, either directly or pursuant to a third-party service contract, the Proposed Capital Project. If any of the Project Owners fails to approve the Proposed Capital Project within thirty (30) days after receipt of the Capital Project Notice, the Project Owners shall exercise commercially reasonable efforts to develop a commercially reasonable alternative (the "Alternative Proposal") which shall be presented to the Shared Facilities Manager within sixty (60) days after receipt of the Capital Project Notice, and the Shared Facilities Manager shall be authorized to proceed with the Alternative Proposal, if any, approved by the Required Majority. If any Project Owner who does not approve such Proposed Capital Project or Alternative Proposal can reasonably demonstrate to the other Project Owners that the Proposed Capital Project or Alternative Proposal is likely to have a material adverse effect upon such Project Owner's Project, the Shared Facilities Manager shall not implement the Proposed Capital Project or Alternative Proposal without the consent of the Project Owner whose Project will be materially adversely impacted. Notwithstanding the foregoing, and for clarity, if the Shared Facilities Manager determines that undertaking the Proposed Capital Project or Alternative Proposal is necessary to address an Emergency (as provided in Section 2.1(a), or if the Shared Facilities Manager determines that the failure to undertake such Proposed Capital Project or Alternative Proposal could cause an Emergency, the Project Owners agree that the Shared Facilities Manager may proceed with the Proposed Capital Project or Alternative Proposal, regardless of any objection or failure to consent by any Project Owner. 2.2 Conditions to Repair or Replacement Project. If the Shared Facilities Manager undertakes a Proposed Capital Project or Alternative Proposal ("Capital Project"), it shall, to the fullest extent commercially reasonable and subject to Prudent Industry Practice, (i) limit any interference with the use by the Project Owners of the Shared Facilities or their Separate Facilities and their Projects during such repair, construction, or installation activities, and (ii) except in the event of an Emergency, (a) schedule during a down-time period if possible, or, as a second choice, during an off-peak period if possible, any required disconnection of the Shared Facilities or Separate Facilities to conduct repair, construction, or installation activities in order to minimize the impact on the Projects of the Project Owners, and (b) provide prior written notice to the Project Owners of commencement of such activities together with a reasonably detailed description thereof, including dates and times of such activities and disconnection, if any. If a Capital Project is required for Shared Facilities that are used by less than all of the Project Owners and the undertaking of such Capital Project disconnects a Project Owner's Project that does not use such Shared Facilities, the Project Owner(s) benefiting from the Capital Project shall reimburse the Project Owner of such disconnected Project for (x) all Net Lost Profits accruing during the period of disconnection arising from the undertaking of the Capital Project and (y) any panel washing at such Project necessitated (as reasonably determined by such Project Owner). The Parties acknowledge and agree that, subject to Section 14.1(a)(iv), (1) the reimbursement of Net Lost Profits and panel washing costs shall be such Project Owner's sole and exclusive remedy with respect to loss of revenue and other Consequential Damages due to the period of disconnection, (2) the actual Consequential Damages arising due to such period of disconnection would be difficult to compute, and (3) the methodology for determining such damages set forth above is a good faith estimate of the calculations used to determine the actual Consequential Damages that would be suffered. The Shared Facilities Manager shall, upon request by any Project Owner, deliver to the Project Owners (A) plans and specifications for any Capital Project, including any Replacement Component and the installation thereof, (B) reasonably satisfactory evidence of all necessary governmental permits for any Capital Project, including if applicable the installation thereof, and (C) reasonably satisfactory evidence of all insurance required for the Capital Project, including builder's risk property insurance, commercial general liability insurance, and workers' compensation coverage for installation labor. 2.3 Warranty Claims. The Shared Facilities Manager shall exercise such Party's rights under the contractor and vendor warranties with respect to the Shared Facilities, and upon the reasonable request of the applicable Project Owners, and subject to their direction and control, the Shared Facilities Manager shall assist them with the exercise of such rights. The Shared Facilities Manager shall (i) monitor and report to the Project Owners concerning the remaining terms of any warranties on Shared Facilities; (ii) perform such inspections as are reasonable to ensure that any final warranty work is not required prior to the expiration of any such warranty, and (iii) subject to the direction and control of the Project Owners, prepare and prosecute warranty claims on behalf of such Project Owners, if reasonably necessary to enforce any such warranties. Subject to the direction and control of the Project Owners, the Shared Facilities Manager shall be primarily responsible for administering the prosecution of the warranty claims requirements under this Section 2.3 on behalf of the Project Owners, and each of the Project Owners shall cooperate with each other with respect to such warranty claims to the extent such Project Owners are the owners and holders of the warranties. All reasonable expenses incurred by the Shared Facilities Manager or any Project Owner in pursuing such warranty claims shall be allocated to the Project Owners in accordance with their respective Pro Rata Share. ARTICLE 3 SEPARATE FACILITIES; SEPARATE PROJECTS 3.1 Separate Facilities. Each Project Owner has procured or may procure, install, and construct certain electrical, communications, and other facilities, structures, fixtures, appurtenances, accessories, machinery, materials, and equipment along and within the Shared Premises, consistent with the Shared Premises Agreements to which such Project Owner is a party, to be owned and used individually by such Project Owner (collectively, "Separate Facilities"). 3.2 Operation and Maintenance of Separate Facilities; Right to Encumber. Each Project Owner shall be responsible for the operation and maintenance of its own Separate Facilities and shall be entitled at any time to mortgage, pledge, collaterally assign, encumber, or grant to any Secured Party a security interest in its Separate Facilities and its rights under this Agreement with respect thereto. 3.3 Conditions to Installation of Separate Facilities. Any Project Owner storing, installing or constructing any Separate Facilities shall, to the fullest extent commercially reasonable and subject to Prudent Industry Practice, (i) limit any interference with the use by the Project Owners of the Shared Facilities or their Separate Facilities and their Projects, (ii) schedule during a down-time period if possible, or, as a second choice, during an off-peak period if possible any required disconnection of the Shared Facilities or Separate Facilities to conduct construction activities in order to minimize the impact on the Projects of the Project Owners, and (iii) provide prior written notice to the Parties of commencement of such construction activities together with a reasonably detailed description thereof, including dates and times of such construction and disconnection, if any. In addition, the Party installing Separate Facilities shall reimburse any Project Owner of a Project for (a) all Net Lost Profits accrued by such Project during the period of disconnection arising from the installation or construction of such Separate Facilities and (b) any panel washing at such Project necessitated (as reasonably determined by such Project Owner) by work relating to the installation or construction of such Separate Facilities. The Parties acknowledge and agree that, subject to Section 14.1(a)(iv), (x) the reimbursement of Net Lost Profits and panel washing costs shall be such Project Owner owner's sole and exclusive remedy with respect to loss of revenue and other Consequential Damages due to the period of disconnection, (y) the actual Consequential Damages arising due to such period of disconnection would be difficult to compute, and (z) the methodology for determining such damages set forth above is a good faith estimate of the calculations utilized to determine the actual Consequential Damages that would be suffered. ARTICLE 4 NONINTERFERENCE 4.1 Continuance of Easement(s) and Other Agreements. Each Party agrees that it will not take any action that results in a breach of the terms of any agreement or covenant related to any Shared Premises or Shared Facilities, including any agreement or covenant in any applicable Shared Premises Agreement. 4.2 No Interference. (a) Each Party shall, to the fullest extent commercially reasonable and subject to Prudent Industry Practices, (i) use the Shared Premises and Shared Facilities (to the extent such Party has a right to use the same hereunder) and such Party's Separate Facilities in a manner that limits any interference with the use and enjoyment by the other Parties of their rights in and to the Shared Premises and Shared Facilities and their separate Projects, and (ii) except in the event of an Emergency, (A) schedule during a down-time period if possible, or, if not possible, during any off-peak period any required disconnection of the Shared Facilities or Separate Facilities to conduct maintenance and repair activities in order to minimize the impact on the Projects of the other Parties, and (B) provide prior written notice to the other Parties of commencement of such maintenance and repair activities together with a reasonably detailed description thereof, including dates and times of such maintenance and repair activities, and any disconnection. ARTICLE 5 ALLOCATION AND PAYMENT OF EXPENSES AND COSTS 5.1 Maintenance of the Shared Facilities. As of the Effective Date, Phase I Owner and Phase II Owner hereby engage the Shared Facilities Manager to, and the Shared Facilities Manager agrees to, perform and provide with respect to the Shared Facilities (and the Shared Premises, to the extent required in connection with the Shared Facilities) professional, supervisory, managerial, administrative and operational responsibilities in accordance with the standards set forth in Section 8.5. Shared Facilities Manager has engaged Algonquin Power Fund (America) Inc. ("Operator") pursuant to that certain Operations and Maintenance Agreement between Operator and Phase I Owner, dated September 18, 2017, as may be amended ("O&M Agreement") to perform the Services (as defined therein) for the Shared Facilities. The Shared Facilities Manager's responsibilities include those service and maintenance obligations included in the O&M Agreement applicable to the Shared Facilities (the "Shared Maintenance"). The costs and expenses incurred by Shared Facilities Manager under the O&M Agreement for the Shared Facilities ("Shared O&M Expenses"), all other costs, expenses, penalties, and liabilities incurred by Shared Facilities Manager, Operator, or Phase I Owner with respect to the Shared Facilities (regardless of whether or not such costs, expenses, penalties, or liabilities are incurred in connection with the O&M Agreement, are payable to Operator or a third party, or otherwise), including real property taxes (collectively, the "Shared Facilities Costs") shall be allocated to each Project Owner in accordance with their respective pro rata share, which as of any date of determination, shall be equal to a fraction (which fraction shall be reduced to a percentage), the numerator of which shall be the nominal nameplate capacity (in MW AC) of such Project Owner's Project, and the denominator of which shall be the aggregate nominal nameplate capacity (in MW AC) of all Projects using the Shared Facilities ("Pro Rata Share"). 5.2 Maintenance and Repair of the Shared Facilities; Shared Facilities Costs. Each Project Owner shall be responsible for its Pro Rata Share of the Shared Facilities Costs and the Shared Facilities Manager shall invoice such Project Owners as set forth herein. Upon becoming a Project Owner and until such Party ceases to be a Project Owner hereunder, each Project Owner shall (a) reimburse the Shared Facilities Manager, on a Pro Rata Share basis, for all reasonable direct labor and other costs and expenses of the Shared Facilities Manager for its activities under this Agreement, including travel, telephone, facsimile, postage expenses, and costs reasonably allocated to the Shared Facilities by the Shared Facilities Manager pursuant to a cost allocation methodology of the Shared Facilities Manager or any of its Affiliates, and (b) pay the Shared Facilities Manager, on a Pro Rata Share basis, an administrative fee of $25,000 per calendar year (prorated for any partial calendar year during the Term and adjusted annually in accordance with the Inflation Adjustment, with the first adjustment taking effect on January 1, 2021), and all such costs, expenses, and fees shall be included in the Shared Facilities Costs. 5.3 Maintenance and Repair of Separate Facilities. Each Project Owner shall be solely responsible for and shall pay all expenses and liabilities relating to the use, maintenance, repair, and inspection of such Project Owner's Separate Facilities ("Separate O&M Expenses"). 5.4 Invoicing, Late Payments. (a) No later than the 20th day of each Billing Period after a Project Owner's Project Owner Effective Date, the Shared Facilities Manager shall send a reasonably detailed invoice to such Project Owner setting forth its Pro Rata Share of the applicable Shared Facilities Costs incurred under Section 5.1 and Section 5.2 for the immediately preceding Billing Period; provided, however, that the Shared Facilities Manager may, in its discretion, require the applicable Project Owners to pay their respective shares of all reimbursable third-party costs either directly to the third party (in accordance with instructions provided by the Shared Facilities Manager) or in advance to the Shared Facilities Manager (for payment by the Shared Facilities Manager to the third party). Payment of the undisputed portion of the invoice will be due and payable within thirty (30) days from receipt of such invoice, or the first Business Day following such day if such day is not a Business Day. Any undisputed payment that is delinquent shall bear interest at the Default Interest Rate. The payment of interest unaccompanied by payment of the delinquent payment shall not excuse or cure any default or delay in such undisputed payment. In the event interest accrues on any undisputed payment that is delinquent, the Shared Facilities Manager shall reflect such amount in each subsequent invoice. (b) If a Project Owner disputes the correctness of any invoice, it shall (i) nevertheless pay the undisputed portion of the net amount of such invoice (but shall not be required to pay the disputed amount) and (ii) concurrently with payment of the undisputed portion, notify the Shared Facilities Manager of the disputed amount with a reasonably detailed explanation of the dispute. Any disputed amount ultimately determined to be due (and any overpayment) shall bear interest at the Default Interest Rate from the date such amount was required to have been made until paid (or from the date of payment until the date of refund in the case of overpayments). 5.5 Property Taxes and Assessments. Upon request from a Project Owner, the Shared Facilities Manager will seek from the Somerset County Assessor an allocation of real and personal property taxes for the Shared Premises, the Shared Facilities, and, if requested by the Project Owner, the Separate Facilities, as applicable for each Project. If a request for an allocation of real and personal property taxes is not made, or if the tax assessor fails to make such allocation, the Shared Facilities Manager shall allocate taxes for the Shared Premises, the Shared Facilities, and the Separate Facilities on a reasonable basis, and the allocation of taxes for the Separate Facilities shall be paid by the applicable Project Owner in accordance with their applicable Shared Premises Agreement. All real property taxes assessed for the Shared Premises and all personal property taxes assessed for the Shared Facilities shall be paid by each respective Project Owner to the Shared Facilities Manager in accordance with its Pro Rata Share and the Shared Facilities Manager shall make the applicable payments in accordance with the Shared Premises Agreements. Each Project Owner agrees to provide the Shared Facilities Manager with such information (including cost information) as the Shared Facilities Manager may reasonably request in connection with making such allocations and payments. 5.6 Costs of Additional Repair Work. The Shared Facilities Manager shall charge the costs of repair of the Shared Facilities, including the cost of procuring and installing Replacement Components, and for other work or services provided by the Shared Facilities Manager under this Agreement for work or services that comprise "Transactional Services" under the O&M Agreement, at cost, and the applicable Project Owners shall be responsible for paying such costs on a Pro Rata Share basis. The Shared Facilities Manager shall invoice such costs in accordance with Section 5.4; provided, however, that the Shared Facilities Manager may, in its discretion, require the applicable Project Owners to pay their respective shares of all third-party costs either directly to the third party (in accordance with instructions provided by the Shared Facilities Manager) or in advance to the Shared Facilities Manager (for payment by the Shared Facilities Manager to the third party). 5.7 Other Expenses Caused By Project Owners. Notwithstanding the provisions of this Article 5, any costs, claims, losses, or other liabilities arising from the actions or inactions of a Project Owner in violation or breach of the covenants herein shall be the responsibility of such Project Owner. 5.8 Rights of Other Project Owners for Non-Payment. If any Project Owner ("Non-Paying Project Owner") fails to timely make any required payment of amounts due under this Article 5, Shared Facilities Manager shall provide written notice to such Project Owner and the other Project Owners within 15 days after such payment becomes past due, and any non-defaulting Project Owner may (but shall not be obligated to) make such payment on behalf of such Non-Paying Project Owner and the amount so paid shall be immediately due and payable from the Non-Paying Project Owner to such other Project Owner, together with interest from the date paid at the Default Interest Rate. 5.9 Metering and Settlement Process. Energy generated by the Projects and flowing through the Shared Facilities will be metered and measured in accordance with the attached Exhibit E ("Metering Process"), which shall be updated to account for any Subsequent Phase Owner simultaneously with the execution of a Joinder by a Subsequent Phase Owner without the need for an amendment to this Agreement. 5.10 Liens. No Party shall, directly or indirectly, create, incur or permit to exist any Lien on the Shared Premises, Shared Facilities or the Separate Facilities except for the following to the extent permitted under such Party's arrangements with its Secured Parties: (a) Solely with respect to the Phase I Owner, (w) any Lien for unpaid taxes that are (i) not yet payable or (ii) that are being contested in good faith by appropriate proceedings, provided that such Lien is fully covered by adequate reserves in accordance with GAAP, or (x) any mechanic's or materialmen's Lien arising in the ordinary course of business, either (i) for amounts not yet due, provided that payment thereof is fully covered by adequate reserves in accordance with GAAP or (ii) for amounts being contested in good faith by appropriate proceedings, provided that either (A) such amount is bonded over pursuant to NRS Chapter 108 and (B) the lienholder's foreclosure action is stayed pending resolution of the proceeding, (y) judgment Liens, provided that such Lien is fully covered by adequate reserves in accordance with GAAP, provided further, that in each case of (w), (x) and (y) above, so long as such proceeding or Lien shall not involve any substantial danger of the sale, forfeiture, or loss of any part of the Shared Premises, Shared Facilities, the Separate Facilities or (z) Liens in favor of such Party's Secured Party pursuant to the Security Documents. (b) Solely with respect to the Phase II Owner or any Subsequent Phase Owner and only to the extent of such Person's right to use the Shared Facilities and such Person's interest in the Shared Premises, (x) any mechanic's or materialmen's Lien arising in the ordinary course of business, either (i) for amounts not yet due, provided that payment thereof is fully covered by adequate reserves in accordance with GAAP or (ii) for amounts being contested in good faith by appropriate proceedings, provided that either (A) such amount is bonded over pursuant to NRS Chapter 108 and (B) the lienholder's foreclosure action is stayed pending resolution of the proceeding, or (y) Liens in favor of such Party's Secured Party pursuant to the Security Documents. If any such Lien not permitted pursuant to this Section 5.10 attaches or a Project Owner receives notice of any such Lien, the Party whose actual or alleged act or omission resulted in such Lien shall cause such Lien to be released and removed from the record within thirty (30) days after such attachment or notice, unless (in the case of any non-permitted Lien on the Shared Premises, Shared Facilities or Separate Facilities) (I) such Party (i) in good faith contests or disputes the claim or claims of the lienholders and the validity of such Liens, (ii) promptly commences legal action to remove such Lien, and (iii) furnishes to the other Project Owners a bond or other security acceptable to the other Project Owners in an amount sufficient to discharge all such contested Liens and (II) during such period the lienholders' proceedings are stayed. Without limiting the generality of the foregoing, and subject to the limitations of authority of the Shared Facilities Manager in Section 7.3 below or otherwise set forth in this Agreement, in addition to the authority otherwise granted herein, the Shared Facilities Manager shall have the power, without further consent or approval of the Project Owners, to do any of the following in the ordinary course of the operation and maintenance of the Shared Facilities: (a) Subject to Sections 7.3(f) and (i), negotiate, enter into on behalf of the Project Owners, and administer agreements with third party contractors, and to otherwise expend monies necessary for the management, operation, maintenance, and repair of the Shared Premises and Shared Facilities in accordance with this Agreement or pursuant to the O&M Agreement; (b) To pay and collect on behalf of the Project Owners amounts due in connection with the Shared Premises and Shared Facilities; (c) To take such action as the Shared Facilities Manager determines to be necessary to address an Emergency; (d) To disconnect any Separate Facilities of any Project Owner, or any Project as a whole, from the Shared Facilities if the Shared Facilities Manager determines, in good faith and in a manner that does not discriminate in favor of any Project or Project Owner, that such disconnection is necessary to avoid material damage to or the unavailability of Shared Facilities; provided, however, that (i) the Shared Facilities Manager will work together with such Project Owner to remedy the situation and reconnect the disconnected Separate Facilities or Project as soon as possible, and (ii) except in cases where the Shared Facilities Manager determines that immediate action is required to address an Emergency, the Shared Facilities Manager will not disconnect or reconnect any Separate Facilities or any Project under this Section 7.2(d) unless (A) it has first engaged a reputable independent engineer acceptable to the affected Project Owner to evaluate the circumstances and such independent engineer determines, as applicable, that such disconnection meets the standard for disconnections forth in this Section 7.2(d) or that such reconnection is prudent, and (B) to the extent possible, it has provided prior written notice of such disconnection or reconnection to affected Project Owners at least 30 calendar days (or such shorter period of time that is practicable if 30 calendar days is not possible) prior to disconnecting or reconnecting such Separate Facilities or Project; and (e) To execute, acknowledge, and deliver any and all instruments and take such other steps as are reasonably necessary to effectuate the foregoing and as are consistent with the terms of this Agreement, including Section 7.3 and any other limitations set forth herein. 7.3 Limitation on Authority. (iii) If any Project Owner delivers a Removal Notice pursuant to Section 8.6(a)(i) and the Shared Facilities Manager disputes the Shared Facilities Manager Event of Default described therein, then within ten days after delivery of such Removal Notice from such Project Owner, the Shared Facilities Manager shall deliver to the Project Owners and their respective Secured Parties, a notice with a detailed description of the reasons why the Shared Facilities Manager disputes such Shared Facilities Manager Event of Default, and within 20 days after delivery of such notice by the Shared Facilities Manager, the Project Owners and the Shared Facilities Manager shall meet and confer in good faith with respect to such Shared Facilities Manager Event of Default. The Shared Facilities Manager shall maintain books and records in sufficient detail to verify amounts due and payable hereunder for a period of not less than three years after the end of the calendar month to which they relate, and all such books and records shall be available for inspection and/or copying by each Project Owner and its Secured Parties or its authorized representative at the cost and expense of such Project Owner and at reasonable times during regular business hours, upon reasonable notice to the Shared Facilities Manager. The Shared Facilities Manager shall have the right to pre-invoice the Project Owners for any materials and components required to be provided hereunder, and, other than as the Shared Facilities Manager determines to be necessary to address an Emergency, not to proceed with the acquisition of such materials and components unless payment has been received by the Shared Facilities Manager for such materials and components. ARTICLE 9 INSURANCE 9.1 Insurance. (a) The Shared Facilities Manager shall maintain "all risk" property insurance coverage in the full amount of the total of all insurable Shared Facilities costs and including a full-replacement cost endorsement an "agreed amount" basis (with no deduction for depreciation or coinsurance penalty), providing, without limitation: (i) Coverage for the Shared Facilities and Shared Premises, including removal of debris, insuring the Shared Facilities against loss or damage by fire, lightning, windstorm, hail, explosion, riot, civil commotion, sabotage, aircraft, vehicles, smoke, other risks from time to time included under "all risk" or "extended coverage" policies, earthquake, flood, collapse, sinkhole, subsidence and such other perils, with a sublimit of not less than $1,000,000 for on-site pollution clean-up required as a result of the occurrence of an insured risk; (ii) Debris removal with a sublimit of not less than 10% of the limit, demolition and increased cost of construction with a sublimit of not less than 10% of the limit and off-site coverage with a per occurrence limit of not less than 10% of the limit or such higher amount as is sufficient to cover off-site equipment for which there have been progress payments; (iii) Transit coverage (including ocean cargo where ocean transit will be required) with a per occurrence limit sufficient to cover the full insurable value of any item in transit but not less than 10% of the limit; (iv) machinery coverage for the Shared Facilities not covered by manufacturer warranty and the infrastructure, defined as the interconnection, substation, circuit breakers, transformers and switches, on a "comprehensive" basis including breakdown and repair with limits not less than full replacement cost of the insured objects. Such insurance coverage shall not exclude resultant damage caused by faulty workmanship, design or materials. Such insurance coverage shall not exclude resultant damage caused by faulty workmanship, design or materials; (v) other coverage common in the industry such as professional services and legal costs, demolition and increased cost of construction, documents and computer records, expediting expense, inflation on incomplete property, leased equipment and rental costs, local authorities clause, removal of debris or other such coverage which is equivalent. (b) The amount of insurance coverage will be increased from time to time as the full replacement value of the Shared Facilities increases. The premiums for such property insurance, and any deductibles or other retention amounts thereunder, shall be Shared O&M Expenses subject to Section 5.2. (c) Each Party shall maintain commercial general liability insurance on an "occurrence" policy form, including coverage for premises/operations, explosion, collapse and underground hazards, products/completed operations, broad form property damage, blanket contractual liability for written contracts, independent contractors and personal injury, for the Project Owner and for contractors, with primary coverage limits of no less than $1,000,000 for injuries or death to one or more persons or damage to property resulting from any one occurrence and a $2,000,000 aggregate limit. Deductibles or self-insured retentions in excess of $50,000 must be approved by the Shared Facilities Manager. Each Project Owner shall name the other Parties as additional insureds and the policy shall contain a severability of interest clause and cross liability. (d) Each Party shall maintain the insurance requirements and policies forth in the Shared Premises Agreements. 9.2 Additional Provisions. Upon and after the Effective Date: (a) Each Party shall provide the other Parties with insurance certificates reasonably acceptable to such other Parties evidencing that its insurance coverages are in compliance with this Agreement. Such insurance and certificates shall (i) name the other Parties as additional insureds under the commercial general liability policies and policies required pursuant to the Shared Premises Agreements to the extent of their respective Pro Rata Share, (ii) provide a waiver of any rights of subrogation against the other Parties, and (iii) indicate that all policies have been endorsed as described above. All policies shall be written with insurers having an A.M. Best rating no less than A-. All policies shall be written on an occurrence basis or claims first-made basis, except as provided in Section 9.2(b). A Party's liability under this Agreement is not limited to the amount of insurance coverage required herein by virtue of this Section 9.2. (b) If any insurance required to be maintained by a Party hereunder ceases to be available on commercially reasonable terms in the commercial insurance market, such Party shall provide written notice to the other Parties, accompanied by a certificate from an independent insurance advisor of recognized national standing, certifying that such insurance is not available on commercially reasonable terms in the commercial insurance market for assets of similar type, geographic location, and design. Upon receipt of such notice, such Party shall use commercially reasonable efforts to obtain other insurance that would provide comparable protection against the risk to be insured, and no other Party shall unreasonably withhold its consent to modify or waive such requirement. (c) Any proceeds of insurance received by a Party under any insurance policy required to be maintained under this Section 9.2 or under the Shared Premises Agreements relating to a casualty event or event of loss with respect to such Party's Project only, may be applied by such Party in its sole discretion, provided that in the event any Project Owner receives proceeds of insurance relating to a casualty event or event of loss with respect to the Shared Facilities or Shared Premises, such insurance proceeds shall be held in a trust account by the Shared Facilities Manager until such loss proceeds are applied to the payment of the costs of repair or restoration of the Shared Facilities or Shared Premises relating to such casualty event or event of loss, in accordance with Section 9.2(d). (d) In the event that all or substantially all of the Shared Facilities or Shared Premises are damaged or destroyed by a casualty event, and provided the proceeds from insurance covering the damage or destruction are sufficient and available to cover the full cost of rebuilding or restoring the Shared Facilities and Shared Premises (excluding the amount of any deductible and/or self-insured retention as specified in the applicable insurance policy), the Shared Facilities Manager shall arrange to restore or rebuild the Shared Facilities and Shared Premises unless the Project Owners unanimously agree not to restore or rebuild the Shared Facilities and Shared Premises. If the proceeds from insurance covering the damage or destruction are not sufficient to cover the full cost of rebuilding or restoring the Shared Facilities and Shared Premises (excluding the amount of any deductible and/or self-insured retention as specified in the applicable insurance policy), the Project Owners shall determine whether to rebuild or restore the Shared Facilities and Shared Premises and, if the Project Owners unanimously elect to rebuild or restore the Shared Facilities and Shared Premises, such costs shall be allocated among, and paid by, all Project Owners in proportion to their respective Pro Rata Shares. If less than all of the Project Owners elect to rebuild or restore the Shared Facilities and Shared Premises, then such costs shall be allocated among, and paid by, the Project Owner(s) that so elect, in proportion to their respective Pro Rata Shares, and any Project Owner who elected not to rebuild or restore the Shared Facilities and Shared Premises shall: (i) have no right to use the Shared Facilities and Shared Premises as replaced or restored and (ii) deliver such bills of sale or other appropriate instruments to the participating Project Owner(s) as the participating Project Owner(s) may reasonably request, transferring to the participating Project Owner(s) the interest of the non-participating Project Owner in, or disclaiming the non-participating Project Owner's interest in, such rebuilt or restored Shared Facilities and Shared Premises. Notwithstanding any election to rebuild and restore the Shared Facilities and Shared Premises as set forth herein, the Parties shall comply with any casualty restoration requirements in the Shared Premises Agreements. 9.3 Condemnation Award. If any Project Owner is granted any award for any condemnation, taking or eminent domain, of the Shared Facilities, such award shall be paid to the Shared Facilities Manager and distributed by the Shared Facilities Manager to Phase I Owner. If any Project Owner is granted any award for any condemnation, taking or eminent domain, of the Shared Premises, such award shall be paid to the Shared Facilities Manager and distributed by the Shared Facilities Manager to the Project Owners in accordance with each Project Owner's Pro Rata Share. Each applicable Project Owner shall have the right to participate in any proceedings with the taking agency pursuant to the provisions of the applicable Shared Premises Agreements. Each Project Owner's consent shall be required for the apportionment of the award to the Grantor (as defined in the Shared Premises Agreements) under the Shared Premises Agreements, or another party or entity, as such process is described in the Shared Premises Agreements. All reasonable expenses, including reasonable attorneys' fees, incurred by any Party in connection with the Assignment or proposed Assignment of such Party's rights under this Agreement shall be paid by the Assigning Party upon request therefor. ARTICLE 11 TERM AND TERMINATION 11.1 Term and Termination. The rights and obligations of the Parties and the Shared Facilities Manager under this Agreement shall commence upon the Effective Date and shall continue until terminated (a) by mutual agreement of the Shared Facilities Manager and the Parties, or (b) in accordance with Section 11.2 ("Term"). 11.2 Early Termination. This Agreement shall automatically terminate, without further action by any Party and without further liability of any Party to any other Party, upon the date that all of the Project Owners have permanently ceased operation of the Projects and such Projects are no longer producing electric energy; provided, that, any and all payment obligations accrued or owing by each Project Owner prior to such termination have been paid. Any Project Owner who wishes to abandon its use of any Shared Facilities may elect to terminate its rights and obligations under this Agreement (such Project Owner a "Surrendering Project Owner"); provided, that, any Surrendering Project Owner shall (a) cure all Events of Default of the Surrendering Project Owner then existing, (b) remove and fully decommission its Separate Facilities, if any at its own cost and expense without disrupting or affecting the Shared Facilities or any other Separate Facility, (c) remain fully responsible for, and shall pay its Surrendering Project Owner Pro Rata Share of, all Shared O&M Expenses and Shared Facilities Costs through the effective date of its surrender of its rights and obligations under this Agreement and shall at all times continue to pay any Separate O&M Expenses with respect to its Separate Facilities and all costs, including reasonable attorneys' fees, incurred by any of the Parties in obtaining required approvals of such surrender and (d) provide any written instruments or agreements reasonably requested by any other Phase Owner(s) in order to memorialize the Surrendering Project Owner's abandonment of the Shared Facilities and the termination of its rights and obligations relating thereto. No surrender of a Project Owner's rights under this Agreement shall relieve the Surrendering Project Owner of any of its obligations under this Agreement or any other agreement entered into pursuant to this Agreement, or its obligations hereunder with respect to its Separate Facilities, unless expressly provided for in this Agreement, or in a writing among the Project Owners. ARTICLE 12 DEFAULT AND REMEDIES 12.1 Events of Default. A Party shall be in material default of its obligations under this Agreement upon the occurrence of one or more of the following ("Event of Default"): (a) Any failure of such Party to pay any amounts due under this Agreement, and such failure continues for more than ten days following the payee Party's notice to such Party of such non-payment; (b) Any purported Assignment of this Agreement by such Party in contravention of the requirements of Article 10; (c) Any other breach, default or failure of performance by such Party (that is not otherwise covered as a separate Event of Default) of any of its obligations, covenants, representations or warranties which is not cured within 30 days following another Party's notice to such Party of such breach, default or failure and which breach, default or failure to perform materially interferes with the operation of the Shared Facilities or materially interferes with the use of a Project or of any Separate Facilities by any non-defaulting Party; (d) Such Party makes an assignment for the benefit of creditors, files a petition in bankruptcy, voluntarily takes advantage of any bankruptcy or insolvency laws or is adjudicated bankrupt or judicially insolvent, in each case, immediately upon such occurrence or, if a petition or an answer is filed proposing the adjudication of such Party as bankrupt, when such Party shall consent to the filing thereof or 60 days after the filing thereof unless the same shall have been discharged, opposed, or denied prior thereto; (e) Any breach by such Party of an obligation in any Shared Premises Agreement to which such Party is a party or by which it is bound, and such breach is not cured within 20 days following a non-defaulting Party's notice to such Party of such breach and which breach materially interferes with the operation of the Shared Facilities or materially interferes with the use the Shared Premises or of a Project by a non-defaulting Party; or (f) Failure by such Party to either obtain or maintain the insurance policies in accordance with Article 9, unless such failure is remedied within 30 days following another Party's notice to such Party of such failure. 12.2 Remedies. Upon the occurrence of an Event of Default, a non-defaulting Party may, after due inquiry that an Event of Default has occurred and is continuing, exercise any and all rights and remedies which a non-defaulting Party might otherwise have at law or in equity (including the right to sue for damages, including damages arising from lost revenues under the non-defaulting Party's Power Purchase Agreement). In addition: (a) Where a Project Owner is the defaulting Party, the Shared Facilities Manager shall have the right to discontinue the use of the Shared Facilities by the Project Owner's applicable Project, provided that the defaulting Project Owner's Project shall be permitted to resume such use promptly when and if (i) the Event of Default is cured (if the Event of Default is capable of cure), and (ii) any and all damage suffered and incurred by the non-defaulting Parties has been compensated; and (b) Where the Shared Facilities Manager is the defaulting Party, any non-defaulting Project Owner shall have the right to remove the Shared Facilities Manager for cause pursuant to the procedures set forth in Section 8.6. 12.3 Equitable Remedies; Self-Help. The Parties agree that damages may be an inadequate remedy for an Event of Default, and that the non-defaulting Party shall be entitled to seek injunctive and other equitable relief, including specific performance, against the defaulting Party to prevent or eliminate such Event of Default. The Parties further agree that if the Shared Facilities Manager materially fails to operate and maintain the Shared Premises or Shared Facilities as required hereunder, the Project Owners may, at the Project Owners' option and with reasonable advance notice to the Shared Facilities Manager and a reasonable opportunity for the Shared Facilities Manager to cure such failure, access such Shared Premises and Shared Facilities and perform such obligations on behalf of the Shared Facilities Manager; provided, that the Project Owners shall not unreasonably interfere with the business operations of the Shared Facilities Manager and shall otherwise perform such operation and maintenance services in accordance with the terms of this Agreement (as if it were the Shared Facilities Manager), including Article 8 hereof. For clarity, any Project Owner that performs the obligations of the Shared Facilities Manager pursuant to this Section 12.3 shall be entitled to the reimbursement of its costs as provided herein (as if it were the Shared Facilities Manager). 12.4 Remedies Cumulative. All of the remedies described in this Article 12 are cumulative and non-exclusive, and the exercise of any one remedy at any one time shall not constitute the waiver of any other remedy at that time or any later time.
